---
import ServicePage from '../../components/ServicePage.astro';

const orgId = new URL('/#organization', Astro.site).href;
const schema = [
  {
    '@context': 'https://schema.org',
    '@type': 'Service',
    name: 'Tour Accounting & Budget Management',
    serviceType: 'Tour accounting',
    description:
      'Tour budget preparation and management for touring artists: projections for wages, per diems, hotels, travel, equipment, rentals and commissions, payroll on the road, and reconciliation of road accounts.',
    provider: { '@id': orgId },
    areaServed: [
      { '@type': 'AdministrativeArea', name: 'Nashville Metropolitan Area' },
      { '@type': 'Country', name: 'United States' },
    ],
  },
];
---

<ServicePage
  title="Tour Accounting & Budget Management | BriBiz"
  description="Tour budgets, payroll, and cash flow for touring artists — projections for wages, per diems, travel, gear, and commissions, and reconciliation back home."
  breadcrumbName="Tour Management"
  heroTitle="Tour Accounting & Budget Management"
  schema={schema}
  related={[
    ['Business management', '/services/business-management/'],
    ['Royalty accounting', '/services/royalty-accounting/'],
    ['Tax services', '/services/tax-services/'],
  ]}
>
  <p>
    We know exactly what it's like to be stuck at a gas station in Idaho and
    needing money–fast. Before BriBiz was a firm, we were on the road ourselves,
    playing thousands of shows and handling the band's finances from the back of
    the bus. Touring is still the heart of most artists' income – and it's also
    where the money gets messiest.
  </p>

  <h2>Before the Tour: Projections &amp; Budgets</h2>
  <p>
    A tour should never be a financial surprise. We create short and long-term
    projections and budgets for touring, including wages, per diems, hotels,
    travel, equipment, rentals and commissions – so you know what the run should
    make, what it will cost, and where the break-even line sits before the first
    van door closes.
  </p>

  <h2>On the Road</h2>
  <p>
    While you're on tour, your artist manager is focused on revenue and exposure.
    But life back home is still happening, and somebody has to think about it.
    That's where we come in: the regular "adulting" that doesn't stop for a tour –
    bank runs, making sure all accounts are flowing as they should, managing
    payroll for your 1099 crew. We especially shine at the scrappy cash flow
    details that come up on the road and back at home. We've been there
    ourselves.
  </p>
  <p>
    Day to day, that looks like keeping wages and per diems moving, paying the
    bills that don't pause just because you're in another time zone, and keeping
    enough cash where it needs to be so a breakdown in Idaho is an inconvenience,
    not a crisis.
  </p>

  <h2>After the Last Show</h2>
  <p>
    When the trailer is unpacked, we reconcile the bank, road and royalty
    accounts – making sure the records and financial statements match what
    actually happened out there, every settlement is accounted for, and the tour's
    real numbers are in front of you. Those numbers feed straight back into the
    next budget, so every tour gets smarter than the last one.
  </p>
  <p>
    Touring money also sets up the rest of your year – it affects your
    <a href="/services/tax-services/">taxes across every state you played</a> and
    the cash flow plan that carries you between runs. Because we handle the whole
    business, none of that falls through the cracks.
  </p>
</ServicePage>
